<h2 class="unnumbered" id="meloidogyne-spp."><em>Meloidogyne</em> spp.</h2>
<p><span>width=0.75</span></p>
<p><img src="LifeCycle03.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span>2</span></p>
<h3 class="unnumbered" id="biology">Biology</h3>
<p>Root-knot nematodes (RKN), <em>Meloidogyne</em> spp., are the most damaging plant parasitic nematodes worldwide. This genus compromises more than 100 species, however, most of the crop yield losses are caused by four of them: the tropical species <em>M. arenaria</em>, <em>M. incognita</em> and <em>M. javanica</em>, and the temperate species <em>M. hapla</em> (<span class="citation" data-cites="Jones2013">(Jones et al. 2013)</span>). The relatively high amount of research done and the accumulated information on the temperate species (<span class="citation" data-cites="Sikora2018">(Sikora et al. 2018)</span>), along with the widened global warming worries, evidence the importance of focusing efforts on the tropical species understanding to effectively design management strategies to control them in the near future.</p>
<p>RKN are obligated parasites that require a host plant to develop its life cycle (Fig. <a href="#fig:Figure101" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure101">[fig:Figure101]</a>). In presence of a suitable root system, the infective vermiform second-stage (J2) juveniles of <em>Meloidogyne</em> moves through soil, up to 75 cm in 9 days on sandy soils (<span class="citation" data-cites="prot1976amplitude">(Prot 1976)</span>), and penetrate the root, usually behind its tip, and migrate intercellularly along the vascular cylinder until is ready to establish its feeding site. Then, nematode secretions transform its surrounding cells into multinucleate and hypertrophied feeding cell, the so-called giant cell. The accumulation of these giant cells cause the characteristic galled tissue present in infected root systems, and for the disturbance of nutrient uptake of plants. Once its feeding site is established, juveniles become sedentary and assume a “sausage” shape as increases its size. J2 then moults through two more stages until reproductive adult stage in ca. 18-20 days. When conditions are favorable, the adult pearl-shaped female remains sedentary and keeps feeding from the giant cells while lays c. 300-500 eggs inside a gelatinous mass, which sometimes can be seen with the naked eye as light brown dots in the surface of galled tissue. Conversely, adult males stops feeding and become vermiform and mobiles. Eventually, males leaves the galls and enter the soil phase in attempt to find a female for sexual reproduction (Fig. <a href="#fig:Figure102" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure102">[fig:Figure102]</a>).</p>
<p><span>width=0.9</span> <img src="Photos05.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span id="fig:Figure102" label="fig:Figure102">[fig:Figure102]</span></p>
<p>Although <em>Meloidogyne</em> species life cycle is considered to differ depending on specie, temperature and host plant, species are also capable to adapt to different temperature conditions. For instance, optimal temperatures of 25-30C and 32-34C were found in populations of <em>M. javanica</em> from Australia and California, respectively (Ferris and Van Gundy, 1979). Such adaptive ability may be one of the main reasons of its success in spreading globally, and also evidence its importance for modern agriculture.</p>
<h3 class="unnumbered" id="economic-importance">Economic importance</h3>
<p>The occurrence of soilborne diseases and pests have increased in recent years as a result of the intensive cultivation needed to supply a growing population in limited land resources (<span class="citation" data-cites="Thies2015c">(Thies, Buckner, et al. 2015)</span>). A comprehensive summary of the estimation of yield losses caused by RKN in several crops have been published by Greco and Di Vito (<span class="citation" data-cites="Greco2009a">(2009)</span>). The cucurbit and solanaceous crops are two of the most severely affected crop families by RKN. Regarding cucurbit crops, maximum yield losses of 88, 53 and 35% in cucumber, zucchini and watermelon have been estimated under greenhouse conditions (<span class="citation" data-cites="Gine2014a">(Ariadna Giné et al. 2014)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Vela2014">(Vela et al. 2014)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Lopez-Gomez2014a">(López-Gómez et al. 2014)</span>, <span class="citation" data-cites="Lopez-Gomez2015a">(2015)</span>). RKN are also one of the most damaging soilborne pathogens in solanaceous crops, specially under protected cultivation (<span class="citation" data-cites="Hallmann2018a">(Hallmann and Meressa 2018)</span>), with maximum yield losses of 94, 95 and 100% reported for pepper, eggplant and tomato, respectively.</p>
<h3 class="unnumbered" id="control-methods">Control methods</h3>
<p>The most commonly used strategy for RKN management has been, until recent years, the use of fumigant and non fumigant nematicides (<span class="citation" data-cites="Nyczepir2009a">(Nyczepir and Thomas 2009)</span>). However, regulations such the European directive 2009/128/EC and the U.S. Clean Air Act (<span class="citation" data-cites="U.S.2012">(US 2012)</span>), have brought special attention on the research and development of environmentally friendlier management strategies.</p>
<p>A promising alternative strategy involves the use of resistant plants, those whose have the ability to suppress infection development, and/or reproduction of plant-parasitic nematodes (<span class="citation" data-cites="Roberts2009">(Roberts 2009)</span>). Besides to have proven to be effective and economically profitable (<span class="citation" data-cites="Sorribas2005a">(Sorribas et al. 2005)</span>), this strategy also reduces the infectivity and reproduction of the nematode, as well as the crop yield losses ((<span class="citation" data-cites="Talavera2009b">(Talavera et al. 2009)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Gine2017b">(A. Giné and Sorribas 2017)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="ExpositoA.2019c">(Expósito et al. 2019)</span>)), even in the following crop (<span class="citation" data-cites="OrnatC1997a">(César Ornat, Verdejo-Lucas, and Sorribas 1997)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Thies2015">(Thies, Ariss, et al. 2015)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Westphal2011">(Westphal 2011)</span>). Despite its advantages, the expression of plant resistance can be affected by several factors, such the genetic background of the plant cultivar and/or the nematode species or population (<span class="citation" data-cites="Cortada2008">(Cortada et al. 2008)</span>). It is common to find virulent nematode populations that are able to overcome the resistant plant defense mechanisms due to its selection after the repeated cultivation of the same resistance gene (<span class="citation" data-cites="Verdejo-Lucas2009a">(Verdejo-Lucas et al. 2009)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Gine2017b">(A. Giné and Sorribas 2017)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="ExpositoA.2019c">(Expósito et al. 2019)</span>). More important, there are only a few resistance genes have been introgressed into commercial cultivar at present, and some of them, such the <em>Mi1.2</em>, reduces its expression at constant temperatures above 30 C (<span class="citation" data-cites="araujo1982effects">(Araujo et al. 1982)</span>). Thus, remarks on the proper use of this strategy and research and development of new genetic sources of resistance must be done. Grafting vegetables onto resistant rootstocks, as an alternative source of genetic resistance, is an effective method to control soilborne pathogens when no commercial cultivars are available (<span class="citation" data-cites="Yetsr2003">(Yetişir, Sari, and Yücel 2003)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Miguel2004a">(Miguel et al. 2004)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Cohen2007">(Cohen et al. 2007)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Thies2016">(Thies et al. 2016)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Kumar2018">(Kumar, Bharti, and Saravaiya 2018)</span>) that was "essentially rediscovered" in the past two decades and quickly expanded to become a common practice at the present (<span class="citation" data-cites="Thies2015c">(Thies, Buckner, et al. 2015)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Kyriacou2017">(Kyriacou et al. 2017)</span>). Application of grafting have expanded mainly in two families: the Cucurbitaceae and the Solanaceae, both of which compromise major vegetable crops. The use of anatomical and physiological compatible graft combinations improve the plant performance under biotic or abiotic stress conditions when compared with that of the ungrafted scion. Although these two factors, along with the increase in yield, have been the main drivers of rootstock selection and breeding, the effect of grafting in fruit quality is also another important factor to have in account (<span class="citation" data-cites="Kyriacou2017">(Kyriacou et al. 2017)</span>).</p>
<h2 class="unnumbered" id="epidemiology">Epidemiology</h2>
<p>To be able to properly design RKN management strategies, there is crucial information that should be acquired by the nematologist with the use of several types of experiments. Given that the expression of resistance can be limited by the genetic background of the plant germplasm, as well as that of the nematode species and populations (<span class="citation" data-cites="Cortada2008">(Cortada et al. 2008)</span>), the response of potential crops must be widely characterized against local populations from the area where it will be cultivated.</p>
<p>As its most evident symptom, the presence of <em>Meloidogyne</em> can be diagnosed by observing root galls on a susceptible host. To evaluate the severity of the disease, a gall index on a scale from 0 to 10 have been proposed, on which 0 = complete and healthy root system and 10 = plant and roots dead (<span class="citation" data-cites="Zeck1971a">(Zeck 1971)</span>; Fig <a href="#fig:Figure103" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure103">[fig:Figure103]</a>).</p>
<p><span>width=0.6</span> <img src="GallIndex02.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span id="fig:Figure103" label="fig:Figure103">[fig:Figure103]</span></p>
<p>The resistance levels of a given plant germplasm can also be categorized in relation to a susceptible standard (<span class="citation" data-cites="Hadisoeganda1982c">(Hadisoeganda 1982)</span>). Expressed as the percentage of RKN reproduction compared to that in a susceptible standard, this parameter is called the reproduction index (RI; Fig <a href="#fig:Figure104" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure104">[fig:Figure104]</a>).</p>
<p><span>width=0.8</span> <img src="RI3.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span id="fig:Figure104" label="fig:Figure104">[fig:Figure104]</span></p>
<p>Moreover, there are also three parameters that serve as indicators of the host status of a potential crop to given local RKN population. These three parameters are usually higher in susceptible than in resistant or poor hosts. To be able to estimate these parameters, nematologist must be capable to determine the relationship between the nematode population density at the beginning (<em>Pi</em>, initial population density) and at the end of the crop (<em>Pf</em>, final population density). These parameters are: (i) the maximum population density (<em>M</em>), the maximum population density achieved by the nematode, (ii) the maximum reproduction rate (<em>a</em>)(<em>Pf/Pi</em> at low densities (<span class="citation" data-cites="Ferris1985">(Ferris 1985)</span>), and (iii) the equilibrium density, that initial population at which nematode receive just enough supply of nutrient to maintain the population density at the same level from begin to the end of the growing season (<math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>P</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>/</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">E, Pf=Pi, Pf/Pi=1</annotation></semantics></math>) (<span class="citation" data-cites="Seinhorst1970a">(Seinhorst 1970)</span>; Fig <a href="#fig:Figure105" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure105">[fig:Figure105]</a>).</p>
<p><span>width=0.7</span> <img src="FigPivsPf.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span id="fig:Figure105" label="fig:Figure105">[fig:Figure105]</span></p>
<p>Equally important, the population growth rate, which can be estimated from the relationship between the <em>Pi</em> and the multiplication rate (<em>Pf/Pi</em>), is another useful indicator that allows nematologist to compare between plant species and/or germplasms, as well as the effectiveness control methods (<span class="citation" data-cites="Talavera2009b">(Talavera et al. 2009)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Gine2017b">(A. Giné and Sorribas 2017)</span>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Exposito2018c">(Expósito et al. 2018)</span>; Fig <a href="#fig:Figure106" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure106">[fig:Figure106]</a>).</p>
<p><span>width=0.9</span> <img src="LogPivsLogPfPi3.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span id="fig:Figure106" label="fig:Figure106">[fig:Figure106]</span></p>
<p>Regarding to crop yield losses useful estimations, there are two parameters that can be calculated by estimating the relationship between increasing levels of <em>Pi</em> and the relative crop biomass or yield according to the Seinhort’s damage model(<span class="citation" data-cites="fdi:010017629">(Seinhorst 1998)</span>): <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mtable><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy="false" form="prefix">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>−</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy="false" form="postfix">)</mo><msup><mn>0.95</mn><mfrac><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></msup></mtd><mtd columnalign="right"><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>i</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mo>&gt;</mo><mi>T</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mtd><mtd columnalign="right"><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>i</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mo>≤</mo><mi>T</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign="right"><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>P</mi><mi>i</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mo>→</mo><mi>∞</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">\begin{aligned}
&amp;y = m + (1 - m) 0.95 ^{\frac{Pi}{T-1}} &amp;&#9;for Pi &amp;&gt; T \\
&amp;y = 1&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;            &amp;&#9;for Pi &amp;\leq T \\
&amp;y = m&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;    &amp;&#9;for Pi &amp;\longrightarrow \infty\end{aligned}</annotation></semantics></math></p>
<p>The nematode population density above which yield loss start to occur is defined as the nematode damage threshold level or the tolerance limit of the crop (<em>T</em>). This value, along with the the minimum relative yield (<em>m</em>) are important parameters to characterize the response of a crop plant to a nematode population. The parameter <em>T</em> manifests itself at small nematode densities and <em>m</em> at larger ones (<span class="citation" data-cites="Greco2009a">(Greco and Di Vito 2009)</span>; Fig <a href="#fig:Figure107" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="fig:Figure107">[fig:Figure107]</a>).</p>
<p><span>width=0.9</span> <img src="Seinhorst.png" alt="image" /></p>
<p><span id="fig:Figure107" label="fig:Figure107">[fig:Figure107]</span></p>
<h2 class="unnumbered" id="watermelon">Watermelon</h2>
<h3 class="unnumbered" id="origin">Origin</h3>
<p>Watermelon, <em>Citrullus lanatus</em> is a diploid creeping monoecious crop that belongs to the Cucurbitaceae family. The taxonomy of the genus Citrullus have had major misapplication of names until recent years, including that os watermelon, <em>C. lanatus</em>, itself (<span class="citation" data-cites="Chomicki2015">(Chomicki and Renner 2015)</span>; <strong>Renner et al., 2014</strong>). The Southern African region is reported to be the center of diversity and probably the center of origin of most of the Citrullus species (<strong>Dane and Lang, 2004; Rubatzky, 2001; Robinson and Decker-Walters, 1997</strong>). However, four hypotheses have been proposed for the origin of watermelon: first, that it descends from the northern African colocynth (<em>C. colocynthis</em>, <strong>Singh, 1978; Sain et al., 2002; McCreight et al., 2013</strong>). Second. that it derives from the South African citron melon, <em>C. amarus</em>, previously referred as <em>C. lanatus</em> var. <em>citroides</em> (<strong>Robinson and Decker-Walters, 1997; Maynard and Maynard, 2000; Rubatsky, 2001</strong>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Chomicki2015">(Chomicki and Renner 2015)</span>). Third, that it stems from the West African <em>C. mucosospermus</em> (<strong>Gou et al., 2013</strong>; <span class="citation" data-cites="Chomicki2015">(Chomicki and Renner 2015)</span>), and fourth, that it both originated and was domesticated in northeastern Africa. Still, more recent research with polygenomic analyses of nuclear gene sequences suggest that the white-fleshed Sudanese Kordophan melon (<em>Citrullus vulgaris</em>) is the closest relative of domesticated watermelon (<strong>Renner et al., 2019</strong>).</p>
<h3 class="unnumbered" id="importance">Importance</h3>
<h5 data-number="0.0.0.0.1" id="section"><span class="header-section-number">0.0.0.0.1</span> </h5>
<p>Watermelon is the most cultivated cucurbit crop.</p>
