<h2 class="unnumbered" id="eggplant">Eggplant</h2>
<h3 class="unnumbered" id="origin-1">Origin</h3>
<h5 data-number="0.0.0.0.5" id="section-4"><span class="header-section-number">0.0.0.0.5</span> </h5>
<p>The Asian eggplant, <em>Solanum melongena L.</em>, is a widely grown species from the Solanaceae family. This crop is the third most widely grown Solanaceous vegetable after potato and tomato, and especially popular in the Southeast Asia and the Mediterranean. Several non-exclusive theories have been proposed regarding eggplant’s origin (<span class="citation" data-cites="Chapman2019">(Chapman 2019)</span>). The general consensus (<strong>Knapp et al., 2013; Weese and Bohs, 2010</strong>) is that the African/Middle Eastern species <em>S. incanum</em> L was transported, intentionaly or otherwise, into Indo-China where the true wild progenitor, <em>S. insanum</em> L., evolved, from which <em>S. melongena</em> is derived.</p>
