<h3 class="unnumbered" id="grafting-1">Grafting</h3>
<h5 data-number="0.0.0.0.9" id="section-8"><span class="header-section-number">0.0.0.0.9</span> </h5>
<p><em>S. torvum</em> is an eggplant crop wild relative (CWR) and is often used as rootstock because of strong resistance to several soilborne pathogens, notably, the RKN (<strong>Gousset et al., 2005</strong>). In order to understand more about the genes involved in RKN resistance, gene expressions analysis was carried out on <em>S. torvum</em> plants with and without infection (<span class="citation" data-cites="Bagnaresi2013">(Bagnaresi et al. 2013)</span>), revealing almost 400 genes which were deferentially expressed under pathogen infection. Gene ontology analysis showed that many of these genes were related to knwon pathogen responses genes, especially chitinases which are often upregulated in plants exposed to nematode infection (<strong>Qtu et al., 2017</strong>).</p>
